Kudos to @joo_sang_lee for leading this work and to all the authors! (9/9)

Our approach's robust success highlights the potential for *major improvement* in transcriptomics-guided cancer treatment. We are excited by the possibilities this opens up in the world of precision medicine. (8/9)
Notably, the most frequently recommended drugs by our approach in the WINTHER cohort were dasatinib, venetoclax, and cobimetinib. (7/9)

Strikingly, we found that *70% of patients* in the WINTHER cohort could have likely become responders if they had been matched to therapies guided by our approach. *94% of patients* could have been matched to more effective therapies overall. (6/9)

Our exciting results led us to ask a compelling question: how many patients would have likely benefited from prescribed drugs if the treatment choices for patients would have been guided by our computational approach? (5/9)

Intriguingly, we found key immune genes such as IFNAR2, IFNGR1, and B2M to be interacting partners of PD1 and CTLA4, and their interactions *effectively* predict response across immune checkpoint therapy datasets. (4/9)
We predicted treatment response in 17 of the 21 targeted- and 8 of the 11 immuno- therapy datasets, with considerable accuracy (AUC > 0.7). (3/9)
To predict treatment outcomes, we defined genetic interaction scores, which capture the likelihood of a given patient responding to a given drug. (2/9)

In a promising step for cancer precision medicine, we devised a novel strategy that identifies genetic interactions and robustly predicts drug response, spanning 21 targeted therapies and 11 immunotherapy datasets across 10 different cancer types (1/9) https://t.co/rXTrFYHImn https://t.co/fXQ5iZz2NS

@dk_barupal @rickdunnblade @CraigWheelock @drupad_t @dbkell @metabolomics Now you are moving the goal posts. Of course knowing the prevalence is important but that does not dictate sample size for a metabolomics study. You always have keep the base rate fallacy in mind when presenting results but that is an easy calculation if you know the prevalence.

@BroadhurstDavid @rickdunnblade @CraigWheelock @drupad_t @dbkell @metabolomics That is indeed for a hypothesis testing situation. A biomarker ROC without the knowledge of a phenotype's prevalence in a target population is useless. If the prevalence is 1%, we will need 10000 samples to show a <5% error rate, unless the population is further narrowed down.

@dk_barupal @rickdunnblade @CraigWheelock @drupad_t @dbkell @metabolomics Low prevalence just makes it harder. That is why we design retrospective nested studies drawn from prospective biobanks. Eg our pre-eclampsia work. Prevalence of 3-5% - had to prospectively collect samples from > 3,000 before we could design a suitably powered metabolomics study.

Combined with present precision oncology approaches, our strategy provides the first systematic framework for analyzing prospective transcriptomics-based clinical trials.
In summary, this is the first computational approach to obtain considerable predictive performance across many different targeted and immunotherapy datasets.
Our genetic interaction score is also associated with the clinical response observed across different cancer types to checkpoint immunotherapies. https://t.co/7Rd02hvFIf

Evaluating this approach retrospectively in a recent multi-arm basket clinical trial (WINTHER), we show that the fraction of patients benefitting from transcriptomic-based treatments could be markedly increased from 15% to 85% by targeting GI-based vulnerabilities in their tumors https://t.co/8pNLvhvH3w

*We emphasize that the treatment outcome info was never used in learning the response predictions and a fixed parameter set was used, thus reducing the well-known risk of over-fitting and the lack of generalizability.*

Overall, through a retrospective analysis of 32 clinical trials of >1500 patients, treated with targeted and immune- therapies, our framework is predictive of response in 25 out of 32 cases (~80%) across 8 different cancer types and 13 therapies. https://t.co/SosQddjc5L
We stratified responders in 8 out of 11 different immunotherapy therapies cohorts (again AUC>0.7) across a range of cancer types, checkpoint targets and inhibitors. https://t.co/U7TfJGCTNW

We stratified responders in 17 out of 21 different targeted therapies cohorts with an AUC>0.7 across different cancer types better than previously published transcriptome-based signatures. https://t.co/8p1EbUjNRI

Current precision oncology is mainly performed by targeting actionable mutations & has a limited patient coverage. Here we present the first approach for systematically guiding patients treatment based on vulnerabilities identified across the whole exome.

We present the first computational strategy leveraging genetic interactions successfully predicting patients response to many different targeted and immunotherapy treatments based on their tumors transcriptome. Sharing the details here- https://t.co/ZcOKwI2uJr https://t.co/iidGFc5xtx

Conclusions:We only solved the problem of how to test bam to clone software/pipelines for our case. Need a public test data set.The AMLs are nice, but very different from breast cancer metastases in mutation and CNA rate. Need diversity across cancers and experimental design.

Also, we were lucky that a recent study used superFreq together with other pipelines in a paper on metastatic breast cancer: https://t.co/HeTtusLDik.This really is the best test, others using the software, and they found that "Results were overall consistent between methods".

Due to the dodgy nature of the manual readouts, we didn't put that plot in the paper (twitter will have to do), and instead pointed to their supp figure 7 and showed examples in our fig 5 and 6.Note gain of the A and B allele of chr8 in Dia and Rel respectively in AML.102! üôÄ https://t.co/TaecIfFall

I think this is a good indication that we produce similar results with the default superFreq "one-click" analysis. Some cases where results differ, I think due to the low mutation rate of AML and threshold effects for pipelines deciding if enough variants to call a clone.

We ran default superFreq on these patients, and made the same scatters. Systematic efforts to promote team science, interdisciplinary collaboration, data sharing and joint experimental/computational training are required for systems biology to reach its full potential.
Application of systems-based models to critical, unresolved questions requires hypothesis-based interrogation, with a focus on translational potential.
Representation and iterative refinement of systems data as models is critical for interpreting and sharing these data sets as tools for biological investigation.
Discovery-based methods, also called -omics approaches, allow for the rapid collection of quantitative data sets, but require careful design, validation and interpretation.
An effective systems study can be framed in three phases: Discovery of the underlying data, Representation of the biological model, and Application to an unresolved question. https://t.co/xZLG7ZA7nU
Systems biology can be a powerful approach for understanding infectious disease and tackling critical, unresolved challenges in medical science.

Finally, this work suggests that studying quantifiable traits in healthy people without disease may be an efficient way of understanding genetic predisposition to disease, even when compared with case/control studies. This has implications for screening and biology. https://t.co/Oq776qpECH

Even among carriers of pathogenic rare variants in titin, a key component of the sarcomere, a polygenic score produced from our common variants still had a significant impact on the function of the heart. This suggests that the common genetic background may influence penetrance.

There have been decades of work elucidating rare variants that drive heart muscle dysfunction. We found that those same regions of the genome were enriched for common variants with a smaller effect in a bigger portion of the population. Blue = expectation, red = observation. https://t.co/9PIFEFZXHN

Thanks to healthy volunteers in the @uk_biobank , we were able to study subtle changes in the heart. Natural variation at a population scale allowed us to identify the regions of the genome associated with heart function and structure. https://t.co/JyCCh49RNQ

Having a high burden of these common genetic variants can predispose people to a specific cause of heart failure (dilated cardiomyopathy). On the low end of the spectrum, we observed that people were at increased risk for a thick-walled heart (hypertrophic cardiomyopathy). https://t.co/DTeQcwn3B4

Excited to share work done with @KrishnaAragam, where we discovered common genetic variants associated with the structure and function of the heart. These common variants, found in healthy people, also influence risk for heart muscle diseases.https://t.co/Drco0OyHzh https://t.co/rGBI7L0etA

We can measure park effectiveness (Aichi Target 11) as a function of vertebrate occupancy. We can target protection effort toward areas of higher wildlife occupancy and measure if those efforts are working.

For me, the key achievement is showing that it is possible to generate a reserve-wide wildlife distribution in just 3 months of leech collecting by minimally trained park rangers (163 of them, sampling 172 patrol areas). This makes it possible to repeat the exercise regularly.

We found that domesticated species (cows, sheep, goats), which are brought into the reserve to graze, dominate the reserve edge, leaving the core, higher-elevation areas for the wildlife (deer are exceptions). "But there's always going to be someone who uses that time to work!!"Yeah, well, they can go right on ahead. I love science, but I love other things too. Doing all of them is what makes me who am I, and a happier person to boot.

It comes with trade-offs, of course. I don't have a TV or home internet. But that's a choice I made about how *I* want to spend the time I have. I look forward to going home and binging podcasts while I paint, or turning on some classical music and reading.
